class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findDisappearedNumbers(int[] nums) {

        // Start from index 0
        int i = 0;

        // Store array length
        int n = nums.length;

        // Cyclic Sort: Place every number at its correct index
        while (i < n) {

            // Correct index for current number
            // Example: 1 -> index 0, 2 -> index 1, ..., n -> index n-1
            int correct = nums[i] - 1;

            // If current number is not at its correct position,
            // swap it with the element at its correct index
            if (nums[i] != nums[correct]) {
                swap(nums, i, correct);
            }

            // If already at correct position (or duplicate exists),
            // move to the next index
            else {
                i++;
            }
        }

        // List to store all missing numbers
        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        // Check every index after cyclic sort
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {

            // If value is not equal to index + 1,
            // then index + 1 is missing from the array
            if (nums[j] != j + 1) {
                ans.add(j + 1);
            }
        }

        // Return all missing numbers
        return ans;
    }

    // Function to swap two elements in the array
    public void swap(int[] nums, int a, int b) {

        // Store first value temporarily
        int temp = nums[a];

        // Put second value at first position
        nums[a] = nums[b];

        // Put first value at second position
        nums[b] = temp;
    }
}
Short Summary
Use Cyclic Sort to place each number at index number - 1.
After sorting, if nums[i] != i + 1, then i + 1 is missing.
Add all such numbers to the answer list.
Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1) (excluding output list).
